Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/gesture back navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom back button handles taps, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** intercepts the Shell back button tap — it replaces the default back action entirely, so your command must call `GoToAsync("..")` explicitly.
- **`OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`** catches swipe-back and hardware back. The deferral is required because `DisplayAlert` is async; without it you'd have a race condition.
- **`args.Cancel()`** prevents the navigation when the user chooses "Stay".
- Set `HasUnsavedChanges = true` in your ViewModel whenever the form is dirty, so both guards know when to prompt.
